    <h1>UMAMI BOY XO (185G) $18, MADE IN SIN&#xAD;GA&#xAD;PORE</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201206/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-06"><time>2020-12-06</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | FOOD &amp; DRINK</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Buy: @umami.boy on In­sta­gram; or­der via link in bio</p>
    <p>In­gre­di­ents: Dried scal­lops, dried shrimp, dried white­bait, ba­con, gar­lic, shal­lots, chilli, soya sauce, su­gar and sun­flower oil</p>
    <p>Score: 19.5/30</p>
    <p>What the judges say: Mr Gooi Khai Shin: “This sauce has a meaty flavour and is very bal­anced.”</p>
    <p>About the sauce: Chef Will Chng, 27, has worked at Meta, Wild Rocket and Roketto Iza­kaya – and has made XO sauce in all these restau­rants.</p>
    <p>“I would say XO sauce is one of my all-time favourite sauces from Can­tonese cui­sine, be­cause of the nat­u­ral umami and savouri­ness from seafood, and that slight smoked flavour from the ad­di­tion of Jin­hua ham – or, in my case, smoky ba­con,” he says.</p>
    <p>“Dur­ing the cir­cuit breaker, when peo­ple were stay­ing home, I thought: Why not of­fer a line of umami condi­ments for peo­ple to en­joy bet­ter food at home? I think of it as shar­ing hap­pi­ness in jars.”</p>

